":"Somme, Picardie, Frankrig","Uwch Dulas, Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1021–":"1021–Overleden","1017–Male":"1017–Overleden","1021–Male":"1021–Overleden","1025–Male":"1025–Overleden","1030–Male":"1030–Overleden","1034–Male":"1034–Overleden","1070–Male":"1070–Overleden","–Male":"Overleden","1030–Female":"1030–Overleden","1051–Male":"1051–Overleden","0999–1056":"0999–1056","0998–1075":"0998–1075","1021":"1021","1075":"1075","1030":"1030","1051":"1051","1070":"1070","1017":"1017","1047":"1047","1025":"1025","from 1035 to 1050":"van 1035 to 1050","1056":"1056","1034":"1034","0998":"0998","0999":"0999","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wales":"Wales","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Frankrijk","Uwch Dulas, Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1021–":"1021–Deceased","1017–Male":"1017–Deceased","1021–Male":"1021–Deceased","1025–Male":"1025–Deceased","1030–Male":"1030–Deceased","1034–Male":"1034–Deceased","1070–Male":"1070–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1030–Female":"1030–Deceased","1051–Male":"1051–Deceased","0999–1056":"0999–1056","0998–1075":"0998–1075","1021":"1021","1075":"1075","1030":"1030","1051":"1051","1070":"1070","1017":"1017","1047":"1047","1025":"1025","from 1035 to 1050":"from 1035 to 1050","1056":"1056","1034":"1034","0998":"0998","0999":"0999","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, France","Uwch Dulas, Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Edrid","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Muslim: variant of   Idris  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Idris","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Mohammad, Ahamed, Ahmed, Beshir, Farouk, Ismail, Jaafar, Mohamed, Omar, Abdalla, Abdulkader, Abubakar.","Muslim: from an Arabic personal name, <i>Idrīs</i>. Idrīs is mentioned in the Koran as a prophet, and many legends are related of him in Arabic folklore and literature. Linguistically, his name corresponds to Hebrew <i>Ezra</i>, Greek <i>Esdras</i>, but the Muslim figure is not the same person as the Biblical prophet of this name. Some legends about him correspond more nearly to those about the Biblical   Enoch  . Compare   Idrees  .","History: Idris ibn-Abdullah (died 793) was founder of the Idrisid dynasty which ruled Morocco from 789–926  AD ."]}]},{"name":"Ithel","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: compound of <i>iud</i> ‘lord, prince’ + <i>hael</i> ‘generous’; borne in the <i>Mabinogi</i> by the son of Llarian."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ithel ap Edrid was born in 1021, in Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Edryd ap Nathan of Wales Wales Brnffenigl, was 22 and his mother, Mrs. Edryd ap Inethan, was 23. He married Mrs. Ithel Ap Edryd in 1047, in Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in Somme, Picardie, France."},"et":{"1021–":"1021–Surnud","1017–Male":"1017–Surnud","1021–Male":"1021–Surnud","1025–Male":"1025–Surnud","1030–Male":"1030–Surnud","1034–Male":"1034–Surnud","1070–Male":"1070–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1030–Female":"1030–Surnud","1051–Male":"1051–Surnud","0999–1056":"0999–1056","0998–1075":"0998–1075","1021":"1021","1075":"1075","1030":"1030","1051":"1051","1070":"1070","1017":"1017","1047":"1047","1025":"1025","from 1035 to 1050":"1035 kuni 1050","1056":"1056","1034":"1034","0998":"0998","0999":"0999","Wales, United Kingdom":"Wales, United Kingdom","Wales":"Wales","Y, Somme, Picardie, France":"Somme, Picardie, Prantsusmaa","Uwch Dulas, Denbighshire, Wales":"Denbighshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1021–":"1021–Kuollut","1017–Male":"1017–Kuollut","1021–Male":"1021–Kuollut","1025–Male":"1025–Kuollut","1030–Male":"1030–Kuollut","10